ustify the validity of their descriptions? Are actors given their own voice? Along the way, Carrard also readdresses questions fundamental to the field, including its necessary membership in the narrative genre, the presumed objectivity of historiographic writing, and the place of history as a science, distinct from the natural and theoretical sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aHistoriographyzFrance. 0aHistoryxMethodology. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aLiterature and historyzFrance. 4aFrench historiography. 4aPaul Ricoeur. 4aconventions of writing. 4afigure of speech. 4ahistoriographic discourse. 4anarrative. 4arepresentation stage. 4arhetorical device. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226428017423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226428017.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles